<TEXT>
as the scope of solidaritys massive 
election victory became clear lech walesa sent some advice to his 
friend president bush keep promoting investment in poland 
then the shipyard electrician who rallied a restless people to 
challenge the communist system got into his blue volkswagen van on 
monday afternoon and drove off down the streets of this proud port 
city 
international labor hero walesa still retains a host of folksy 
touches nearly nine years after strikes at the lenin shipyard that 
spawned solidarity catapulted him to fame and a nobel peace prize 
he walked with wife danuta and 19yearold son bogdan to 
cast his ballot at city polling station no 169 in sundays 
historic elections 
a young woman outside the polling station gave him a red rose 
and praised his tireless efforts 
walesa replied with a smile well i didnt do all this just 
for myself 
like many busy men wrapped up in their work walesa has trouble 
taking time off 
we hope you can go on vacation you deserve it the rev 
henryk jankowski a close adviser told him as 3000 people cheered 
outside st brygidas church we hope you can go to america 
only half of jankowskis wish is officially scheduled now 
walesa is heading to the united states this fall for a speech to 
the aflcio and most likely another meeting with bush 
in fact bush is heading over to the walesas for lunch next 
month 
there the president will sit down to a traditional polish meal 
with the 45yearold walesa his wife and at least some of the 
couples eight children in a pleasant residential area outside 
central gdansk 
this is a rehearsal for bushs visit walesa said with a 
hearty laugh as he acted as host at a private party on election eve 
at his singlefamily home on 54 polanki street 
bush will sit at a plain wooden table surrounded by paintings 
of nature scenes and religious motifs 
when walesa shows bush into the living room the president will 
see a picture of pope john paul ii on the wall my highest 
authority is the way roman catholic walesa refers to his 
polishborn hero and mentor in the vatican 
bush and walesa met when bush as vice president visited warsaw 
in 1987 a photograph of the two conferring adorns the wall outside 
walesas office in the gritty local headquarters of solidarity two 
blocks from the shipyard 
like any folk hero walesa has his trademarks the handlebar 
mustache the solidarity badge the black madonna of czestochowa 
pin on his lapel 
less wellknown is his bluntness 
on monday the labor federation leader wearing a blue 
sportcoat bulldozed through reporters seeking a statement from him 
on election results 
walesa said the voting shows poles want very big reforms but 
also cautioned we have to keep searching further to solve the 
nations woes 
then he bounded up the steps back into the st brygidas rectory 
to cap a victory he has been seeking along with his larger 
successes assuring the future of the lenin shipyard 
in what he called an act of providence polishborn american 
multimillionaire barbara piaseckajohnson stepped in with a promise 
of a huge investment to rescue the ailing yard from a 
governmentordered shutdown 
after lunch with mrs piaseckajohnson her advisers and members 
of the communistpicked shipyard management monday walesa used the 
occasion to promote the next phase of his cause reform of polands 
faltering and often chaotic economy 
all our political victories will mean nothing if we dont 
improve the economy said walesa 
poland faces constant shortages of consumer goods spare parts 
and food items many poles disillusioned with the countrys plight 
seek work in west germany the united states and elsewhere 
to ease the situation poland has been seeking to attract 
foreign investment the bush administration recently began leading 
the cheers for polands success in that area 
what mrs piaseckajohnson is doing is a continuation of what 
president bush has already told us walesa said in reference to 
us administration support for polish economic reforms she is 
fulfilling it immediately 
so i am sending a personal letter through her to the president 
in which i thank him for wanting to meet poland halfway walesa 
said 
walesa then handed mrs piaseckajohnson a plain white envelope 
containing the letter for bush as news photographers cameras 
clicked and tv cameras whirred 
