<TEXT>
the general accounting office has concluded 
that the chief medical officer of the veterans administration did 
not try to improperly dictate the outcome of a study of death rates 
in va hospitals an agency spokesman said monday night 
however the study does conclude that expressions of concern by 
dr john gronvall over the impact of such a study on the va image 
led some people to believe he was giving such instructions 
said don smith a spokesman for the department of veterans affairs 
successor to the va 
sen alan cranston dcalif chairman of the senate veterans 
committee asked for the gao investigation after the washington 
post reported last october that gronvall had ordered a change in 
methodology to lower the percentage of va hospitals showing 
abnormal death rates 
the newspaper reported results of the study in tuesday editions 
the telephone number listed for the author of the study was 
answered by someone who said he no longer lives there 
smith said he had seen a copy of the gao report earlier in the 
day 
gronvall was travelling and could not be reached but judging by 
his letter to gao contained in the report commenting in the 
findings i think he feels somewhat vindicated said smith 
the dispute arose when another va staff member the late dr 
francis e conrad argued in memos that chaging the study methods 
could be seen as self serving 
the issue is what statistical cutoff to use in judging whether 
death rates are within the normal range of variation only six of 
the vas 172 hospitals 35 percent would be judged to have 
abnormal death rates if the analyst wants to be 99 percent sure 
that the determination is not the result of normal fluctations but 
if the analyst wants to be 95 percent sure 12 hospitals or 7 
percent would be judged to have abnormal death rates 
va began the study after the health care financing 
administration found that 25 percent of the nations private 
hospitals had abnormally high death rates 
smith said va and the financing agency kept records differently 
and the percentages arrived at by the two studies could not be 
compared 
the veterans department plans to release its study next week 
using both statistical cutoffs smith said 
</TEXT>
