<TEXT>
a railroad and a fuelshipping 
company announced plans monday to reimburse residents of a 
neighborhood stricken by twin disasters last month 
the deal outlines community reparations promises 5000 for 
each family evacuated assures residents that the site is safe and 
calls for a study of utilities in the area 
for the calnev pipe line co the agreement cleared city 
objections to plans to replace its 14inch diameter petroleum fuel 
line which exploded in a deadly fireball on may 25 about two 
weeks after a southern pacific train derailed on may 12 
four people including two residents were killed in the 
derailment and two residents were killed in the pipeline 
explosion dozens more were injured in the explosion 
national transportation safety board investigators have focused 
on the possibility that the outofcontrol freight damaged the 
nearby pipeline as it vaulted from the tracks 
the plan was announced jointly by city officials executives of 
calnev and the southern pacific transportation co and us rep 
george e brown of san bernardino 
no court would have ordered them to do what theyve agreed to 
do today city attorney james penman said the question now is 
whether this is going to be finalized 
one of the things city officials had sought was immediate 
assistance for displaced families and penman said that 5000 
reimbursement really helps 
the 5000 is to be paid to each family that returns to their 
home calnev officials said the payments estimated to total about 
750000 would begin wednesday 
what the agreement is today is a first crack at getting 
started said anthony j andrukaitis vice president of gatx 
terminals calnevs corporate owner it is nowhere near a 
comprehensive settlement 
the companies tentatively agreed to reimburse the city for 
overtime paid for police fire and other emergency personnel 
continue to pay for housing and meals for displaced families and to 
buy the homes that were destroyed or severely damaged 
the new pipeline will buried at least six feet deep twice the 
federal standard and covered with concrete for 600 feet the length 
of the rail disaster area andrukaitis said 
if we can get the new line in by wednesday wed test it 
thursday and possibly be operating by friday andrukaitis said 
mayor wr holcomb said monday that 95 homes out of the 178 that 
were evacuated would be immediately reopened for residents return 
all the environmental and safety experts agree on the safety 
and integrity of the area holcomb said 
the city attorney emphasized calnevs support for a federal 
study of the placement of gasoline natural gas pipelines and other 
vital utilities in the greater san bernardino area if the study 
recommends moving the calnev fuel line the company has agreed to 
do it penman said 
the proposed engineering study would examine the sort of 
juxtaposition that apparently played a role in the double disasters 
