<DOCNO> AP890606-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
house members have flooded the rules committee 
with more than 100 proposed amendments to savings and loan bailout 
legislation dimming the chances of floor action this week 
the bush administration which announced its sampl proposal on 
feb 6 and challenged congress to act within 45 days has shown 
increasing impatience with the pace of action in the house 
the rules committee chaired by rep joe moakley of 
massachusetts the ranking democrat after the death last week of 
former chairman claude pepper is scheduled to consider the sampl 
legislation on tuesday 
it will decide which amendments will be considered by the full 
house when it takes up sampl legislation written by the banking 
judiciary and ways and means panels 
house majority leader thomas foley dwash told moakley last 
week that he wants the rules panel to finish work tuesday so the 
house can take up the bill on wednesday 
however nearly 50 house members have asked to speak to the 
rules committee and the panel must wade through more than 109 
amendments a difficult task to achieve in one day 
if the rules committee finished work wednesday the full house 
could begin debate on thursday but since the chamber is out of 
session on friday any vote likely would be delayed until next week 
the senate passed this thing on april 19 and the losses in 
sampls have grown by over 500 million since that date said 
assistant treasury secretary david w mullins 
the industry is just hemorrhaging out there and every day they 
delay passage costs at least 10 million he said 
more than half a dozen of the amendments under consideration 
would weaken what the administration considers the key change in 
the bill a requirement that sampl owners invest at least 3 in 
tangible or real money capital for every 100 in lending a 
high capital level acts as a buffer absorbing losses before 
federal deposit insurance kicks in 
rep frank annunzio dill chairman of the house banking 
subcommittee on financial institutions had planned to offer an 
amendment that would allow regulators at their discretion to 
count supervisory goodwill as tangible capital but pulled back 
after the administration decided to oppose it 
the washington post reported in tuesday editions that rep james 
quillen rtenn planned to urge the rules committee to allow the 
house to vote on an amendment that would weaken restrictions on 
counting goodwill as tangible capital it said the measure would 
benefit several hundred sampls including heritage federal savings 
loan of kingsport tenn where quillen has at least 200000 on 
deposit 
wendell kirk chief executive of the sampl was quoted by the 
newspaper as saying that without the amendment the institution 
would have to come up with cash to replace 28 million in goodwill 
it currently counts as capital kirk was quoted as saying he asked 
quillen to sponsor the measure 
kirk said the amendments effect on quillen would be minimal 
perhaps 250 and added if you try to pin a conflict on him it 
would be criminal it would be low down quillen was quoted as 
saying in my mind there is no conflict of interest efforts 
to reach him by telephone monday night were unsuccessful 
supervisory goodwill is an accounting break offered by 
regulators in the early 1980s to institutions that took ailing sampls 
off the governments hands 
annunzio argues that it is unfair to penalize sampls who took the 
accounting break at the governments urging however the 
administration argues that it is unfair to taxpayers to allow the 
institutions with supervisory goodwill to operate with none of 
their owners money at risk 
annunzio and other house members from illinois including 
republican leader bob michel met with treasury and white house 
officials last thursday in attempt to secure the administrations 
support for their compromise amendment however mullins said the 
proposal is simply not acceptable to us 
as an alternate annunzio will back an amendment by rep henry 
hyde rill that would permit institutions with goodwill to use 
administrative appeals to delay the imposition of tougher capital 
rules for up to 18 months 
other amendments before the rules committee would if permitted 
to reach the house floor reopen virtually every major battle 
already fought in the committees that wrote the bill 
several amendments would delete provisions designed to help 
provide housing to poor people others would weaken the requirement 
that the sampl industry contribute 300 million a year to pay 
interest on government bailout borrowing 
</TEXT>
