<TEXT>
the amoco pipeline that spilled crude oil 
into the yampa river last week is among hundreds of miles of 
colorado pipelines exempted from government safety inspections 
officials say 
the oil industry persuaded the reagan administration in 1985 to 
drop all federal maintenance inspections of that type of oil 
pipeline known as a gathering line 
as a result the us department of transportations office of 
pipeline safety no longer conducts regular checks on the amoco 
line which leaked about 10000 gallons of light crude friday into 
the yampa river in northwestern colorado but an amoco spokesman 
said the company meets federal standards on such lines 
the spill was declared contained sunday and much of the oil 
that was not contained broke up or was washed away in the swiftly 
flowing river officials said but they said there still could be 
longrange effects on the environment that part of the river is 
home to three endangered fish species 
traces of the spill were found as far away as 100 miles 
downriver from the site 
jack overly who oversees oilpipeline inspections in 12 western 
states from the transportation departments denver regional office 
said he didnt have figures on the number of miles of pipeline were 
exempted from regulation but he estimated the total as 1000 miles 
in colorado alone 
if this leak was caused by corrosion we definitely could have 
had an effect on this pipeline if it still were subject to 
federal regulation and inspection overly said 
amoco executives said the company still does not know what 
caused the leak but overly noting that the leak occurred where 
the pipeline passed beneath the river said rust is the first 
thing i would suspect 
the 6inch line carried more than 100000 gallons of crude oil a 
day 
a gathering line generally links an oil field with storage tanks 
the transportation department still inspects about 500 miles of 
oil pipelines in colorado overly said those pipelines are called 
transmission lines and they generally link refineries with major 
distribution points 
amoco spokesman jack rigg confirmed that the 106mile pipeline 
involved in the leak linking an oil field near craig with storage 
tanks in wamsutter wyo is subject to no state or federal 
inspections 
he said amocos policy on maintenance is to comply with 
federal regulation on all company pipelines even though the 
regulations no longer apply to gathering lines 
he said the line at craig was inspected in 1985 and repaired in 
1986 
overly said that reagan administration officials exempted 
gathering lines from federal regulation after oil executives said 
the pipes didnt pose serious threats to public health because most 
pass through remote terrain 
