<DOCNO> AP890606-0076 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a decoy drug designed to hopelessly confuse the 
aids virus by mimicking its natural target is safe and may lower 
levels of the lethal virus inside the body researchers said 
tuesday 
scientists said they were encouraged by the results but they 
cautioned that testing is at an early stage and no one can be sure 
how effective the medicine will be in stopping aids 
nevertheless this represents an exciting step forward said 
dr ian weller of middlesex school of medicine in england 
the drug is known as soluble cd4 and it is one of more than a 
dozen currently being used experimentally against the aids virus 
so far only one medicine azt has been approved by the us 
food and drug administration for use against hiv the aids virus 
while it can prolong the lives of people with aids it does not 
cure the disease and it has a variety of toxic side effects 
its clear that we desperately need alternative treatments to 
azt said dr thomas merigan of stanford university 
reports on cd4 and other potential aids drugs were presented at 
the 5th international conference on aids the major annual meeting 
to review progress against the epidemic 
dr james mason us assistant secretary for health said 
progress in drug development is another success in our war 
against this terrible infection 
mason also it is increasingly important to set up voluntary 
programs to contact sexual partners of hivinfected people so they 
will know of their risk of catching the virus 
cd4 is one of a growing group of medicines that are specifically 
designed to exploit the builtin weaknesses of the aids virus 
in this case the medicine is a synthetic copy of a molecule 
called cd4 these molecules cover the surface of a particular 
variety of blood cells known as helper t cells 
these cells orchestrate the bodys immune system and they are 
the chief targets of hiv the virus finds them by zeroing in on cd4 
researchers reason that by flooding the bloodstream with copies 
of cd4 the virus will mistakenly attack these decoys and miss the 
blood cells 
in preliminary studies on 18 people at the national cancer 
institute doctors found that shortterm treatment with cd4 
appeared to reduce the amount of virus in their bodies by about 50 
percent 
however dr robert yarchoan who directed the study cautioned 
that such fluctuations can occur naturally and might not have 
resulted from the drug none of the patients got better during the 
19day experiment 
the results could have been better but they could have been a 
lot worse yarchoan said i still have a lot of enthusiasm for 
this approach it has one of the best chances of therapeutic effect 
with the least toxicity of anything being discussed right now 
a second preliminary study conducted on 30 patients at san 
francisco general hospital and new england deaconess hospital in 
boston found no clear evidence of viral reduction 
the two studies were intended primarily to determine how large a 
dose of the medicine can be safely given 
dr j davis allan who led the study at the boston hospital 
said i am very encouraged that the drug appears to be safe the 
study was not designed to detect subtle degrees of efficacy we may 
have not reached the effective dose yet 
researchers hope to make cd4 last longer in the bloodstream by 
chemically welding it to part of an antibody they also have 
developed another hybrid that joins cd4 with a poison a 
combination that might kill infected cells that make virus inside 
the body 
merigan said that 17 experimental aids drugs are being given to 
7000 patients in studies sponsored by the us national institutes 
of health and tests of six more will start soon 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

