<TEXT>
workers kept pumping gas into a leaking pipeline 
for nearly an hour after it already had blown to pieces spawning a 
fireball that engulfed two trains and turned scores of people into 
ash staterun media said tuesday 
soviet news reports said at least 190 people died in the 
pipeline blast early sunday morning on the transsiberian railroad 
about 750 miles southeast of moscow 
some of the 762 people who were hospitalized with injuries from 
the blast are expected to die according to television news program 
vremya it said said half of the injured had burns over more 
than 70 percent of their bodies 
more than 200 people still were missing and some officials said 
the final death toll could reach 500 
health minister yevgeny chazov told the government newspaper 
izvestia that the third and fourth days are the most critical for 
burn victims and that soviet doctors lack experience in treating 
such severe burns 
this lack of experience obviously is complicating our work 
he said 
izvestia said doctors had determined 170 injured children needed 
special equipment to help them breathe and that they were 
appealing for advice and urgent airlifts of equipment from west 
germany japan the united states and italy 
a spokesman for us industrialist armand hammer said 10 kidney 
dialysis machines were being sent from the united states 
the blast occurred when a pipeline carrying a highly flammable 
mixture of benzene propane and butane sprang a leak filling a 
forested valley with concentrations of gas the gas was ignited by 
a spark from one of the two trains on the transsiberian line 
nearby 
