the accomplishments of the 100th congress will remain forever a 
monument to your leadership 
and to the great leaders of the republican party gerald ford 
who left this place to assume the presidency as a healing president 
in a difficult time in our history john rhodes and bob michel 
and all of my colleagues past and present whose vision of the 
country though sometimes sharply different was marked by a common 
commitment to public service shared concern for improving the 
common good and a love of this house 
we are proud to call this the peoples house the fundamental 
institution of american democracy 
although it is not the oldest parliament in the world it has 
existed longer as an independent popularly elected legislature than 
any other parliamentary body in history 
as we watch the remarkable struggle of people in china and the 
growing aspirations of the people in the soviet union poland and 
elsewhere to take control of their destiny we should take great 
pride that the values that gave this institution its birth and which 
have flourished here and sustained us for two centuries now sweep 
around the world 
this body reflects most closely the nation at large 
it is not as many have suggested a fixed stagnant body 
it is constantly refreshed by new members from every corner of 
the country who have brought their ideas and energy to bear on 
behalf of the people they represent 
only 7 percent of the houses current members were in the house 
when i was first elected in 1964 
eightyone percent of the current members have been elected since 
1974 
more than half of the current members 55 percent have been 
elected since 1980 
the constant change in membership is a source of great strength 
for the house but fundamentally and more importantly the house 
reflects the will of the electorate 
our business here is the peoples business 
it is time to put divisiveness behind us to reach out and 
address the issues of national policy that members of both parties 
