<TEXT>
the food and drug administration said tuesday 
it planned a 50fold reduction in the amount of lead permitted to 
reach beverages from ceramic pitchers because of new evidence that 
extremely small amounts of lead can hurt children 
lead at concentrations tolerable by adults can limit body growth 
and intelligence of children and can cause brain damage and behavior 
problems 
lead in pitchers comes from the glaze commonly used to make 
ceramics smooth and impervious 
officials are most concerned about acidic liquids like orange 
juice eating away at the glaze and causing lead to leach small 
cream pitchers would not be subject to the new standard since they 
are not used for acidic liquids 
the fda is proposing to allow pitchers to be sold only if they 
leach no more than 01 micrograms or onetenth of a millionth of a 
gram of lead per milliliter of an acidic test solution currently 
pitchers are allowed to leach up to 5 micrograms of lead per 
millileter 
the proposal also would require that highlead decorative and 
commemorative ceramic plates have fired into them a permanent 
warning that cautions not for food use may poison food or 
have holes so they cant be used for food 
the current standard was set by fda in 1979 based on 
recommendations of the world health organization however as a 
result of the recent studies the federal centers for disease 
control and the who have reduced their recommended maximum levels 
the proposed regulation was published in the federal register 
last thursday after a 60day comment period the fda will issue 
final rules 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

