<DOCNO> AP890606-0105 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
two major studies of the airline industry put 
radically different slants on the impact of airline hub operations 
on competition and air fares 
a study by the general accounting office to be released at a 
senate hearing wednesday says airlines charge an average of 27 
percent more per passenger mile on flights to and from 15 major hub 
airports than at other airports included in the study the 
associated press obtained an advance copy of the study 
but a study by the airline industry released tuesday says average 
airline fares have decreased since deregulation of the industry in 
1978 and fares at 30 hub airports are only 15 percent above the 
industry average that study says hub fares are a little higher 
primarily because hubs tend to have more nonstop flights 
both studies are to be discussed on wednesday at a hearing of the 
commerce science and trasporation subcommittee on aviation which 
is examining the airline practice of feeding many of their flights 
through a single airport 
the study by the gao which is the investigative arm of congress 
concludes the trend that has seen major airlines dominating flights 
at airports where they set up hub operations has decreased 
competition 
many travelers have less choice among airlines as more markets 
are being controlled by a single airline the study says 
the report says that although the number of destinations served 
from hub airports studied increased 10 percent between may 1985 and 
may 1988 most of the increases were by dominant carriers and were 
offset by large service reductions by other carriers 
at 13 of the 15 hubs studied average air fares per passenger 
mile were higher for dominant carriers than for other airlines 
serving the same airports the report said 
hubbing generates important operating efficiencies but it can 
also lead to substantial market power for the airlines which could 
lead to higher fares and reduced levels of service gao official 
kenneth m mead said in testimony prepared for the subcommittee 
hearing 
the industry study conducted by the aviation consulting firm of 
simat helliesen amp eichner concludes that competition in individual 
markets has increased despite the greater concentration within the 
industry and at some airports 
the study commissioned by the air transport association which 
represents major airlines concludes there is little if any 
relationship between average fares and airline concentraiton at 
either hub or nonhub airports 
the hub and spoke system has evolved into a highly competitive 
national transportation system which provides enormous benefits to 
the american public said robert aaronson ata president 
the ata study says better service such as more nonstop flights 
account for average fare levels at some hubs that are higher than 
the industry average 
but in analysing the study the association said passengers are 
not hostage to the higher fares because cheaper options are 
available including multistop flights or connecting flights 
airline schedules at 25 nonhub airports show they are now served 
by nearly twice as many airlines as in 1978 when the airline 
industry was deregulated the ata study said 
the ata study includes charts which show that in 1978 nearly half 
of all airline passengers traveled in markets where a single carrier 
had 70 percent or more of the flights but in 1988 only 20 percent 
of passengers traveled in markets that were served by only one 
airline 
the growth of the number of hubs and the expansion of service 
at them have had astonishingly beneficial consequences for the 
typical spoke community the ata said 
</TEXT>
