<TEXT>
imprisoned black leader nelson 
mandela was allowed a visit tuesday from govan mbeki the 
highestranking african national congress member at liberty in south 
africa 
mbeki 78 received unexpected permission for the visit after 
being turned down several times since his release from prison in 
november 1987 
it is not known what the veteran black nationalists discussed 
because mbeki is barred from being quoted by the press no other 
source of information was available 
mbeki spent about 2 hours at victor verster prison farm in 
paarl outside cape town but the exact length of his meeting with 
south africas most popular leader was not disclosed the two last 
met shortly before mbeki was freed 
they were among eight african national congress leaders sentenced 
to life imprisonment in 1964 for plotting to sabotage the government 
farida omar an antiapartheid activist from cape town said she 
was with mbeki when he received a telephone call tuesday morning 
informing him the visit had been approved 
he was very thrilled she said 
rumors of mandelas possible release have been circulating in 
south africa for more than a decade and the government gives no 
firm indication of its plans however the decision last year to 
move him to a suburbanstyle ranch house on a prison farm revealed 
the special status he has even as an inmate 
mandela 70 has refused offers of freedom on condition he 
renounces the use of violence in the fight to topple the whiteled 
government 
there is speculation that mandela may be released after national 
elections in september for whites indians and people of mixedrace 
the 28 million blacks have no vote in national affairs 
mbeki was freed unconditionally because he was ailing but a 
month later was placed under harsh restrictions prohibiting him from 
leaving his hometown of port elizabeth without permission he has 
been allowed periodic visits to cape town for medical treatment 
</TEXT>
