<TEXT>
bush administration officials and lawmakers 
clashed tuesday over legislation calling for ussoviet 
negotiations to ban the superpowers production of plutonium the 
material used in nuclear weapons 
under questioning from members of the house armed services panel 
on department of energy nuclear facilities administration officials 
also conceded that the united states has the ability to detect work 
at soviet reactors that manufacture plutonium 
dont we have the technical ability to pick up a largescale 
plant in the soviet union said rep ron wyden dore one of the 
house sponsors of the international plutonium control act 
after calling the question difficult to answer in an open 
session troy e wade ii the energy departments acting assistant 
secretary of energy for defense programs said 
we can determine if the facility is operating or not operating 
period 
wyden and rep bill green rny testified before the panel on 
behalf of the legislation that seeks to compel the administration to 
pursue the negotiations by threatening to block operation of some 
us nuclear weapons facilities 
identical bills introduced in the house and the senate say that 
six months after enactment president bush would be prohibited from 
operating any of the facilities dedicated to production of plutonium 
for military purposes unless he certified one of the following 
conditions 
the soviet government refuses to negotiate a ban on plutonium 
and highly enriched uranium 
the united states is unable to determine whether the soviets 
have halted production or 
the soviets continue to get plutonium by operating civilian 
plants 
us facilities geared to plutonium operation are either 
mothballed or closed permanently in the soviet union 14 reactors 
produce enriched uranium and plutonium for the nuclear arsenal 
although last month kremlin leader mikhail s gorbachev announced 
that he would shut down by the end of the year three of 14 reactors 
that produce enriched uranium and plutonium for the soviet nuclear 
arsenal 
the many congressional cosponsors of the international 
plutonium control act have in effect asked the administration to 
call secretary gorbachevs hand on the plutonium issue and negotiate 
a mutual and verifiable end to production wyden said 
green said that when secretary of state james a baker iii met 
with gorbachev early last month the kremlin leader expressed a 
desire to work on a bilateral agreement on controlling production of 
all weapongrade fissionable materials 
we should call his bluff green told the committee 
but kathleen c bailey assistant director of the us arms 
control and disarmament agency argued against the legislation 
saying the absence of us facilities dedicated to plutonium 
production versus the more than 10 soviet reactors would force bush 
to negotiate from a position of weakness 
in addition this legislation would undermine us capability 
to make strategic nuclear materials in support of our nuclear 
deterrent hampering our capability to produce nuclear weapons 
before we cease to rely on them is dangerous and destabilizing 
bailey noted that the soviet nuclear program does not separate 
military and civilian facilities while the united states does if 
the soviets decided to break out of the ban they could send 
us inspectors home and turn their facilities and plutonium 
stockpile to weapons purposes 
the administration argument prompted rep james bilbray dnev 
to question whether the united states would have to build up its 
capacity so we can break out 
bailey responded the united states must negotiate from strength 
saying that was the case on the ussoviet treaty to eliminate 
intermediaterange nuclear missiles 
