grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on 
the chicago board of trade despite increased sales of wheat to 
china 
mondays announcement that china has purchased 185 million 
metric tons of wheat sent wheat prices higher in early trading 
today but prices moved lower as trading progressed 
the wheat sale apparently had been negotiated over the previous 
two weeks said jerry gidel an analyst with lit america inc in 
chicago 
despite the announcement of the sale analysts say there is 
concern the turmoil in china could disrupt industry and commerce in 
that huge commoditytrading nation 
corn prices were higher despite word that egypt and turkey have 
made major corn purchases from france instead of the united states 
soybean prices were mostly higher although the strong dollar is 
expected to continue to hamper export sales 
at the open wheat was 1 cents lower to cent higher with the 
contract for delivery in july at 394 a bushel corn was a cent 
lower to cent higher with july at 264 a bushel oats were a 
cent lower with july at 168 a bushel and soybeans were cent 
lower to 3 cents higher with july at 709 a bushel 
