<DOCNO> AP890606-0177 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the chairman of the senate finance committee 
is asking his colleagues to scrap president bushs child care tax 
credit proposal in favor of a plan that would help parents pay for 
their childrens day care and health insurance 
in a memo sent to committee members monday and obtained by the 
associated press sen lloyd bentsen dtexas proposed making the 
current dependent care tax credit that is available to low and 
moderateincome families refundable in advance a new credit up 
to 500 a year would be created to help pay for health insurance 
for children under age 19 
bentsen said the proposal would cost the treasury 116 billion 
over the next five fiscal years 
he said the loss could be offset by added revenue the government 
will reap when tax credits now extended to troubled financial 
institutions expire next year and by making permanent the 3 percent 
federal telephone excise tax the phone tax is scheduled to drop to 
2 percent on jan 1 1990 
in the memo bentsen asked committee members to vote on the plan 
wednesday however because of other senate business he postponed 
that action until next week and called off a planned news 
conference at which he was to outline the legislation 
bentsens childrens initiative would replace the 25 
billion taxcredit plan offered by bush but is not intended to 
undermine a separate childcare bill sponsored by sen christopher 
dodd dconn 
senate aides said bentsen wanted his taxcredit package to be 
passed in conjunction with the final version of dodds bill 
the dodd bill would provide federal funds for more child care 
slots and set minimum federal standards for day care centers most 
republicans vigorously oppose the regulatory provisions of the dodd 
measure and senate aides said they believed bentsen wanted to keep 
his measure as separate legislation to improve its chances of 
passage unless a bipartisan agreement is reached on an overall 
childcare package the subject of current negotiations 
bentsen in the memo said making the existing dependent care 
credit refundable would provide cash for poor families who owe no 
taxes and who therefore would not benefit from a normal credit 
against tax liability 
bush in his childcare bill also suggested making the existing 
dependent care tax credit refundable 
the president also proposed a new tax credit of up to 1000 a 
child initially for families with incomes of between 8000 and 
13000 with the credit phasing in and by 1994 becoming available 
to familes with incomes of up to 20000 
in outlining that proposal to a house committee last month 
labor secretary elizabeth dole took a swipe at dodds plan 
the child care needs of working americans can best be met by 
providing assistance to parents not to providers through state 
and local regulations not federal standards through 
communitybased and publicprivate partnerships not federal 
bureaucracies and by parental involvement not federally mandated 
procedures 
critics of the bush plan while applauding the presidents 
motives have said that creating a new credit and making parents 
choose between it and the existing credit would only confuse 
parents and perhaps cause them to avail themselves of neither 
indeed a treasury department tax expert at the hearing with mrs 
dole had trouble explaining the mechanics of the bush proposal to 
the committee 
bentsen made no mention of the bush proposal in his memo but 
aides said he believed broader application of the existing credit 
was a better approach than creating a duplicative approach 
the new health insurance credit proposed by bentsen would allow 
families with incomes of 12000 or less to receive a tax credit 
for up to 50 percent of the cost of insurance premiums for a child 
under the age of 19 the maximum credit would be 500 families 
with incomes between 12000 and 21000 would be eligible for a 
reduced credit with the exact amount to be determined by income 
the health insurance credit which would become effective in 1991 
could be paid out in advance if the taxpayer desired the money up 
front 
bentsen also proposed allocating 25 million a year for the next 
five years through the department of health and human services 
for a program under which the federal government would pay up to 50 
percent of the costs of programs to provide basic health care to 
uninsured children under age 19 and their families 
</TEXT>
