<TEXT>
the european commission said tuesday it 
will consider whether to continue antidumping measures against 
us imports of propylene alcohol a propanederived product used 
in making printing ink paints and cosmetics 
the us producers of propylene alcohol are union carbide corp 
of danbury connecticut eastman chemical international co 
kingsport tenn which is part of eastman kodak co and hoechst 
celanese corp a subsidiary of west germanys hoechst ag 
current antidumping measures against imports of us propylene 
alcohol were first decided in april 1984 they were due to expire 
last year but will be kept in force until the new investigation is 
completed the european commission said 
according to a commission statement the antidumping case was 
reopened at the request of the european council of chemical 
industry federations cefic a brusselsbased group representing 
more than 80 percent of eec production of the chemical 
cefic has alleged that us producers export their product at 
about 10 percent below their internal market price according to 
european producers us production capacity of 92000 metric tons 
a year exceeds us internal demand by about 65000 tons 
cefic said us export of propylene alcohol to the eec has risen 
to 14762 tons in 1988 worth roughly 10 million from 6758 tons 
in 1985 even with the antidumping measures 
under the current measures the us companies have undertaken 
not to undercut european companies pricing in the eec 
</TEXT>
