<TEXT>
cnw corps board of directors today approved a 
16 billion buyout offer made by a corporation including cnw 
management ending a twomonth hostile takeover bid by japonica 
partners 
the corporation was formed by blackstone capital partners lp and 
includes donaldson lufkin amp jenrette inc a new yorkbased 
securities firm and the union pacific corp cnw officials said 
japonica announced in new york it was terminating its bid 
because of the deal and said it would decide whether to sell some 
or all of its cnw shares 
the agreement calls for acquisition of cnw by blackstone and a 
management group led by company chairman and chief executive 
officer robert schmiege for 4550 per share in cash and 450 per 
share of payinkind preferred stock with a 17 percent dividend 
rate 
blackstone a private new york investment banking firm will 
hold a controlling interest in cnw under the agreement 
the transaction valued at 16 billion is based upon 
approximately 19 million cnw shares outstanding and the assumption 
of cnw debt 
the offer was approved by a special cnw board committee that was 
evaluating bids for the chicagobased rail company 
cnw is the parent of the chicago and northwestern transportation 
co a 6000mile railroad with 8500 employees that operates in 
nine states most of them in the midwest 
japonica cnws largest shareholder with an 88 percent stake 
has been attempting a takeover since april 27 japonicas 
44ashare offer values cnw at 722 million 
new yorkbased japonica is headed by two former goldman sachs 
co investment bankers paul b kazarian and michael lederman 
japonica officials did not immediately return telephone calls 
seeking comment 
bethlehem pabased union pacific railroad relies heavily on 
the north westerns chicagotofremont neb line for eastwest 
freight traffic the union pacific accounts for about 40 percent of 
the north westerns shipments analysts say 
union pacific recently paid 15 million for an option to buy 
the iowa interstate railroad a regional line between iowa and 
chicago officials said the line would have served as a substitute 
to the north western should a hostile takeover disrupt freight 
service 
officials of japonica had said they planned to sell cnws real 
estate excess equipment and chicagoarea commuter lines if their 
takeover bid was successful 
the railroads union on friday made a proposal to buy the 
company that would have given employees a onethird stake in the 
railroad 
