<TEXT>
congressional efforts to force the 
nations thrifts to meet stringent capital requirements would push 
almost onethird of the industry into insolvency and keep home 
mortgage rates above 10 percent the chief economist for a trade 
association said tuesday 
james christian director of the economics department for the 
us league of savings institutions told texas thrift executives 
that as many as 973 thrifts with 768 billion in assets would fail 
to meet requirements that they maintain 3 percent tangible capital 
the industry has been pushing for capital requirements which 
either include goodwill the amount of net worth above the 
value of tangible assets or a severalyear period to transform the 
goodwill into money 
opponents have objected to including goodwill because it is 
intangible 
speaking at the 1989 texas savings and loan league convention 
christian said many lawmakers apparently feel more is better and 
tougher is what they want to do but he said it is a mistake if 
you have to kill a third of the industry in order to get this done 
the day after tomorrow 
christian said more stringent capital requirements would force 
institutions to shrink causing them to sell off mortgages which in 
turn would tighten the market and keep interest rates high he 
predicted home mortgage rates will average 11 percent this year 
falling only slightly to 106 percent by 1991 
but christian said the 2000 remaining thrifts that would not be 
affected by the more stringent requirements are plain vanilla 
housing lenders for the most part always have been 
critics have blamed much of the industrys problems on savings 
and loans that strayed too far from their roots as home lenders 
this year alone regulators have placed more than 200 thrifts 
under their control awaiting passage of legislation that would 
provide more than 157 billion over the next 10 years to rescue the 
industry 
the us house favors the more stringent capital requirements 
but the legislation is not expected to come up for a floor vote 
before next week as the house rules committee sifts through more 
than 100 amendments 
in other forecasts christian said the current business 
expansion already the nations longest during peacetime could 
continue at moderate levels for up to two years but for that to 
happen he said the federal reserve system must stop worrying about 
inflation 
until recently the fed has been pushing up interest rates to 
keep inflation under control but christian said world markets are 
forcing the fed to rethink that strategy through the strength of the 
dollar 
christian said the inflation rate will rise to 48 percent this 
year before falling to 40 percent by 1991 
later m danny wall chairman of the federal home loan bank 
board told the group that figures to be released wednesday indicate 
the evaporation of deposits from the nations thrifts continued to 
decline in april a traditionally down month as taxpayers pay uncle 
sam 
in april 1988 thrift deposits grew by 12 billion as investors 
shifted money from uncertain stock and mutual fund investments so 
far this year however 285 billion has been withdrawn from 
thrifts including a record 108 billion in january 
wall also said that a secret survey by the bank board found some 
southwest plan thrifts not doing enough to sell distressed real 
estate 
most federal regulators who have visited texas in recent months 
have taken pains to reassure local officials that the government 
will not dump on the market properties acquired through the rescue 
of hundreds of savings and loans and banks 
but wall told reporters tuesday the bank board had sent 
shoppers into texas and discovered that some of the properties 
held by institutions recapitalized last year through the southwest 
plan had not even been listed for sale 
wall suggested that the southwest plan thrifts which were 
created last year through the consolidation and sale of ailing 
institutions may have taken the no dumping promise too 
literally 
